Title: Time-Domain PSOLA Concatenative Speech Synthesis Using Diphones  
Author: Jon R.W. Yi 
Keyword: Key terms: concatenative speech synthesis, diphone, pitch-mark, pitchtrack, pitch period, prosodic contour, time and frequency modification  
Web: http://www.sls.lcs.mit.edu/jonyi/  
Address: Cambridge, Massachusetts 02139 USA  
Affiliation: Spoken Language Systems Group Laboratory for Computer Science Massachusetts Institute of Technology  
Abstract: A method for a time-domain Pitch-Synchronous Overlap-and-Add (PSOLA) concatenative speech synthesis system was developed using diphones as the synthesis units. After a search algorithm selects an optimal sequence of units based on phonetic and prosodic continuity (includes phone labels, pitch, duration, and energy) across unit boundaries, PSOLA techniques are applied to combine the units into a synthetic waveform. Informal listening tests determined the speech to be of fair quality. As this method is flexible and scalable, possible applications include generic synthesizers and voice conferencing systems. Future research may include plans to produce more natural sounding speech, integrate the system into a network synthesis server, and derive intonation patterns from algorithms in DECtalk. 
