Reference-contexts: Recently, time-domain concatenative speech synthesis algorithms have become prominent, because of their low computational requirements compared to frequency-based methods. The most popular methods stem from a family of Overlap-and-Add (OLA) algorithms <ref> [5] </ref>. Algorithms of the OLA family have opened the door to more natural-sounding concatenative speech synthesis, because real speech sub-units can now be employed. The branch of OLA algorithm to be considered in this work include the Pitch-Synchronous Overlap-and-Add (PSOLA) variants, which operate at the pitchmark level. <p> Specifically, the Time-Domain PSOLA (TD-PSOLA) algorithm will be used for our concatenative speech synthesis system, as it is effective at performing simultaneous warping in pitch and duration <ref> [5, 8] </ref>. The speech synthesis unit to be used in conjunction with TD-PSOLA is the diphone, a virtual unit of speech which partially spans two phones. The main reason for its appropriateness in concatenative speech synthesis is that it attempts to capture co-articulation between two phones.
